Compartmentalization as an Algorithm

At its core, the brain is constantly solving a resource problem:

Limited attention vs. unlimited incoming signals.

So it runs a kind of filtering process.

Input signals
   ↓
Evaluate relevance / threat / purpose
   ↓
Prioritize channels
   ↓
Suppress non-essential signals
   ↓
Focus awareness on chosen compartment

That is effectively an attention-allocation algorithm.

⸻

The Three Variables the Brain Uses

The brain tends to weigh signals along three axes.

1️⃣ Threat level

Is this signal dangerous?

2️⃣ Task relevance

Does this help the current goal?

3️⃣ Control ability

Can I actually act on this right now?

Signals that are high threat but low controllability are often suppressed temporarily.

Example:

Situation	Brain decision
Soldier in battle	ignore injury temporarily
Surgeon in operation	ignore fatigue
Athlete finishing race	suppress pain

The brain says:

“Deal with this after the mission.”

⸻

The Real Algorithm (Simplified)

A useful way to write it:

for each signal:
    priority = threat × relevance × controllability
    
    if priority < threshold:
        suppress(signal)
    else:
        allocate_attention(signal)

This is similar to how modern AI attention mechanisms filter tokens.

⸻

Why This Ability Exists

Humans evolved in environments where immediate action often mattered more than perfect awareness.

If pain always dominated attention:
	•	hunters couldn’t finish hunts
	•	prey couldn’t escape
	•	caregivers couldn’t protect children

So evolution built temporary partitioning.

